    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-04-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-04-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="718"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d718">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Press Release Issued by the Department of State, April 13,
                        1933</hi>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d718fn1">Reprinted from Department of State,
                            <hi rend="italic">Press Releases</hi>, April 15, 1933, p. 247.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1933-04-13">April 13, 1933</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>David P. Johnson, American Collector of Customs at Port-au-Prince, has confessed
                    that he has been guilty of defrauding the Haitian <pb facs="0877" n="789"
                        xml:id="pg_789"/> customs and accepting bribes from Zrike Bros., importers
                    and merchants of Port-au-Prince. The fraud consisted in underweighing the bales
                    of merchandise consigned to the importers, duties being payable on the weight of
                    each package. Suspicion was aroused several months ago that these frauds were
                    being committed, as a result of which a thorough investigation was instituted by
                    the General Receiver of Customs, Mr. de la Rue. This investigation indicated
                    that Johnson was implicated in the frauds.</p>
                <p>As a result of Johnson’s confession, the Department of State on April 11
                    instructed the Legation<note n="2" xml:id="d718fn2">See telegram No. 24,
                        below.</note> to inform the Haitian Government that it was willing to waive
                    Johnson’s immunity as a treaty official and surrender him to the jurisdiction of
                    the Haitian courts. Johnson has accordingly been surrendered to their
                    jurisdiction.</p>
            </div>
